Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

This data set contains information about 10,000 movies collected from the Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue. I analyzed the dataset based on the questions below.

Question(s) for Analysis¶

The following questions were used to analyze the Movie dataset:

  • Which year has the highest number of movie released in the last 20 years in dataset?
  • Which year has the highest or lowest movie budget in the last 20 years?
  • Which year has the highest or lowest movie revenue in the last 20 years?
  • Which movie has the highest or lowest votes?
  • How many movie titles are above the 75th percentile revenues in 2015?

Summarily, the dataframe (df_tmdb) contains precisely 10,866 rows and 21 columns. It is both messy and dirty due to the following:

  • The release_date column datatype is string instead of datetime.

  • There were missing values in some of the columns.

  • There is one duplicate row in the dataset.
    • </ul> In addition, the entire columns of the dataframe are not neccessary considering the scope of the investigation questions.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Activity:Investigation questions were attended to in this section. Dataset was explored to draw out insights, inferences and conclusions which can be pivotal to better decision making.

General Dataset Inspection¶

In [20]:
# The distribution of data in the columns were assessed with histogram chart
df_tmdb_edited.hist(figsize=(15,15));

From the histogram charts, it was observed that budget, revenue, popularity and vote_count are right skewed, while release_year is left skewed and vote_average seem to be normal. It can be deduced generally that revenue, budget, popularity and vote_count individual distributions are alike and might have some relationship and impact on movie production every year.

In [21]:
#The relationship accross the columns were accessed using scatter_matrix function.
pd.plotting.scatter_matrix(df_tmdb_edited, figsize = (15,15));

Based on the scatter graph plots showing the relationship across the columns, it is revealed that some of the columns have positive correlation with one another. Such as popularity-revenue, budget-revenue,budget-vote_count,revenue-vote_count, etc. While release_year-revenue, popularity-release_year are negatively related.

In [49]:
#Yearly original title (movie) count derived to obtain number of movies released yearly
bar_height=last_20_years.groupby('release_year')['original_title'].count()

#Function defined subsequent plotting of similar bar charts
def bar_chart(bar_height):
    return bar_height.plot(kind='bar', figsize=(10,10))

#Function called to plot graph
bar_chart(bar_height)
plt.title('Number of Movies Released in the Last 20 Years',fontsize=18)
plt.ylabel('Number of Movies', fontsize=18)
plt.xlabel("Release Year", fontsize=18);

According to the bar chart above it can be deduced that the number of movies released increased across the years. The highest number of movies were released in year 2014. But what could be responsible for this hike in movie release and does it translate to higher revenue?

Which year has the highest or lowest movie budget in the last 20 years?¶

In [50]:
#Mean budget for each year assigned to x
bar_height=last_20_years.groupby('release_year')['budget'].mean()
bar_chart(bar_height)

#Bar chart plotted to see relationship
plt.title('Yearly Movie Budget in the Last 20 Years',fontsize=18)
plt.ylabel('Budget', fontsize=18)
plt.xlabel("Release Year", fontsize=18);

According to the bar chart above it can be deduced that the budget rate decreased across the years. 2014 which has the highest number of movies released has the the lowest budget rate. Whereas, year 1999 in which there was lowest movies released had the highest budget for movies. This suggests that number of movies released could have an inverse relationship with budget.

Number of movies released each year is not a column in the dataframe but can be listed out from last_20_years.groupby('release_year')['original_title'].count()in previous question and assigned to number_movies_released This was plotted against corresponding yearly average budget assigned to Average_budget_per_year in a scatter graph to determine relationship.

How many movie titles are above the 75th percentile revenues in 2015?¶

In [62]:
# The dataframe was queried to focus on year 2015
film_release_2015 = df_tmdb_edited.query('release_year == 2015')

# A histograph was plotted to see the distribution of revenue in 2015
film_release_2015.revenue.plot(kind='hist', figsize=(10,10))
plt.xlabel('Revenue')
plt.ylabel("Frequency")
plt.title('Revenue Distribution');

This distribution indicates that data is right skewed and therefore more movies have revenues within the 25th percentile

np.percentile(film_release_2015['revenue'],75)

film_release_2015.query('revenue >= 3286448.0')['original_title'].count()

In [64]:
# The distribution of data for 2015 in the columns were assessed with histogram chart
film_release_2015.hist(figsize=(10,10));

The general distribution of data in columns in 2015 resembles the distribution when all the years were considered especially the last 20 years. The same factors: budget, vote_count, popularity and revenue are interelated.

Conclusions¶

Summarily, a total of five questions were used to investigate the dataframe, The Movie Database. The investigation carriedout on the movies database revealed the following findings:

  • Year 2014 has the highest number of movies released in the last 20 years.
  • The year 2014 has the lowest movie budget, the highest being year 1999. An inverse relationship occurs between number of movies released yearly and budget.
  • The year 2014 has the lowest movie revenue, the highest being year 1997. An inverse relationship also exists between number of movies released yearly and revenue.
  • The movie title Inception has the highest vote count and about 476 movies share the lowest count.
  • It was gathered that 158 movie titles are above the 75th percentlile of revenue.

Limitation:

The limitation of this dataframe is that there were columns that has missing values that are strings and cannot be augmented with measures of central tendency values like mean, median or mode. If the data were augmented, it would likely enhance the investigation and improve findings.
